After the Free International Order
CAMBRIDGE – Many analysts see the free international order as having ended with China’s rise and US President Donald Trump’s election.
But should Joe Biden, if he defeats Trump in November, try to bring it back?
Maybe not, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are right to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither genuinely global nor always very liberal.
It excluded more than half the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and included many authoritarian states.
US hegemony has been overrated.
Nevertheless, the strongest country must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided – and Americans will suffer for it.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to establish rules-based international institutions with different member countries participating in different areas.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 21st century, both failed to balance against US power, while the US was obsessed with pursuing freedom values at the expense of sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without UN Security Council approval.
It also supported a UN General Assembly resolution in 2005 on the "responsibility to protect," aimed at providing protection for citizens subjected to brutal treatment by their own governments – which the US then invoked in 2011 to justify bombing Benghazi to protect citizens there.
Critics have portrayed this record as US arrogance in the post-Cold War era – for example, when Russia and China felt duped by NATO's intervention in Libya that ultimately led to regime change – while defenders have described it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, the growth of Chinese and Russian power has more strictly limited the scope of liberal interventionism.
What remains then?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereignty principles enshrined in the UN Charter, according to which nations can only go to war for self-defense or with Security Council approval.
Since 1945, the occupation of a neighbor’s territory by force has been rare, and when it does occur, it comes at an exorbitant cost due to sanctions (as in the case of Russia’s annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council regularly authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, while political cooperation has successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rules-based order remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism had fueled an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the WTO.
The result will be a decoupling of global supply chains, especially in situations where national security is at stake.
While China complains about the US blocking Huawei and other companies from building 5G networks in the West, the US position aligns with sovereignty concerns.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules would help prevent de-coupling from escalating.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
By contrast, interdependencies in the ecological realm create insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty because threats are transboundary.
No matter how globalization is undermined economically, environmental globalization will continue because it follows biological and physical laws, which contemporary geopolitical logic cannot affect.
These issues threaten everyone, but no single country has the capability to solve them independently.
On issues like the 2019 pandemic and climate change, power also has what one might call a positive-sum dimension.
Under such circumstances, thinking only about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also consider exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization benefit us and everyone else.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this did not impede Sino-US cooperation.
Biden faces the challenge of whether the US and China can collaborate on creating global public goods while competing in traditional great-power rivalry domains.
The internet is a new and important issue – because it is partly of a transnational nature but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As the Global Commission on Internet Governance recommends, certain rules to prevent tampering with the basic structure of the internet may also be in the interest of authoritarians if they wish to achieve connectivity.
However, when they use proxies to wage information warfare or interfere in elections (which violates sovereignty), norms must be strengthened through agreements similar to those negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalations of maritime incidents (even though ideological animosities still exist).
The US and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and build the necessary deterrence.
Holding to the free values of cyberspace does not mean unilaterally disarming the US.
Instead, the US should distinguish between legitimate forms of public persuasion soft power and hard power such as covert information warfare, and it must retaliate when the latter is employed against it.
Public broadcasting and radio can be allowed for Russia and China, but secret united actions like manipulating social media are not.
Moreover, the US will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Polling shows that US public opinion wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values these principles.
If Biden is elected, the question he faces is not whether to restore the free international order.
The question is whether the US can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also collaborating with a broader set of countries to manage the rule-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
